## 🔒 How Pessimistic Locking Works

### Step-by-Step Flow

```
Cashier 1                          Cashier 2
   │                                  │
   ├─ BEGIN TRANSACTION               │
   │                                  │
   ├─ SELECT ... FOR UPDATE           │
   │  (Acquires lock) 🔒              │
   │                                  │
   ├─ Read stock: 100                 │
   │                                  ├─ BEGIN TRANSACTION
   ├─ Check: 100 >= 30 ✅             │
   │                                  ├─ SELECT ... FOR UPDATE
   ├─ Update: 100 - 30 = 70           │  (Waits for lock...) ⏳
   │                                  │  ⏳ Blocked
   ├─ COMMIT                          │  ⏳ Waiting
   │  (Releases lock) 🔓              │  ⏳ Still waiting
   │                                  │
   │                                  ├─ (Lock acquired!) 🔒
   │                                  │
   │                                  ├─ Read stock: 70 (updated value)
   │                                  │
   │                                  ├─ Check: 70 >= 40 ✅
   │                                  │
   │                                  ├─ Update: 70 - 40 = 30
   │                                  │
   │                                  └─ COMMIT
   │                                     (Releases lock) 🔓
   │
   ▼                                  ▼
Final Stock: 30 ✅ (CORRECT!)
```

### SQL Generated

**Cashier 1:**
```sql
BEGIN;

-- Acquire lock
SELECT * FROM inventory 
WHERE product_id = 123 AND tenant_id = 'tenant-1'
FOR UPDATE;

-- Update
UPDATE inventory 
SET quantity = 70, updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 456;

COMMIT;
```

**Cashier 2 (waits until Cashier 1 commits):**
```sql
BEGIN;

-- Waits here until Cashier 1's lock is released
SELECT * FROM inventory 
WHERE product_id = 123 AND tenant_id = 'tenant-1'
FOR UPDATE;

-- Now reads updated value (70)
UPDATE inventory 
SET quantity = 30, updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 456;

COMMIT;
```

